<p>Italy&#x27;s highest court has approved the handover of a Ukrainian national accused of coordinating the 2022 Nord Stream pipeline sabotage, a decision announced by the suspect&#x27;s lawyer on 19â€“20 November 2025. German authorities say the man will face charges in Berlin including collusion to cause an explosion, sabotage and destruction of infrastructure tied to the 2022 blasts. The ruling clears the legal step for transfer to Germany and is a notable development in the multiyear international investigation into the Nord Stream attacks.</p><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Court mechanism: Italy&#x27;s Supreme Court of Cassation upheld a lower-court verdict authorising the extradition, completing the domestic judicial step required for handover</li><li>Specific charges: German prosecutors plan to charge the suspect with collusion to cause an explosion, sabotage and destruction of infrastructure, legal counts linked directly to the 2022 pipeline blasts</li><li>Suspect background: Reports identify the man as a former Ukrainian military officer, a detail cited by multiple news outlets covering the extradition decision</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Defense (lawyer Nicola Canestrini): The suspect&#x27;s lawyer publicly announced that Italy&#x27;s top court approved the handover, signalling the legal decision but not commenting on evidence in open reporting. (<a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/top-italian-court-approves-handover-of-ukrainian-nord-stream-suspect-to-germany'>Straits Times</a>)</li><li>German authorities: Prosecutors in Germany have framed the case as crimes including collusion to cause an explosion and sabotage linked to the 2022 Nord Stream explosions, and intend to try the suspect in Berlin. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2025/11/20/italy-to-extradite-ukrainian-nord-stream-sabotage-suspect-to-germany'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/top-italian-court-